WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.520
Hi, I'm Carson, and I'm an engineer at RStudio, and I'd like to show you some work we've been

00:00:10.520 --> 00:00:14.920
doing to make custom theming easier inside of Shiny and RMarkdown.

00:00:14.920 --> 00:00:17.719
I'd like to show you two different packages.

00:00:17.719 --> 00:00:24.260
The first is bslib, which allows you to essentially style any of the components that are rendered

00:00:24.260 --> 00:00:28.540
by your web browser inside of an app or a document.

00:00:28.540 --> 00:00:34.220
The second, thematic, allows you to essentially translate the CSS styles that you include

00:00:34.220 --> 00:00:40.459
in your browser and allow them to set new defaults for your static R plots.

00:00:40.459 --> 00:00:45.220
So to start using bslib with Shiny, the first thing that you're going to want to do is to

00:00:45.220 --> 00:00:51.380
call this bstheme function to create a theming object, which you can then give to the theme

00:00:51.380 --> 00:00:58.660
argument of essentially any page layout inside of Shiny that wants to utilize Bootstrap.

00:00:58.660 --> 00:01:04.419
Now at least currently, by default, what this is going to do is actually upgrade your application

00:01:04.419 --> 00:01:08.940
from using Bootstrap 3 to using Bootstrap 4.

00:01:08.940 --> 00:01:13.680
So if you happen to put this inside of an existing application and you encounter any

00:01:13.680 --> 00:01:20.779
issues, just know that you can also downgrade to Bootstrap 3 when using the bslib package.

00:01:20.779 --> 00:01:24.339
In the future, we plan on supporting Bootstrap 5 and higher.

00:01:24.339 --> 00:01:29.279
And regardless of what Bootstrap version you're using, you can easily customize the main colors

00:01:29.279 --> 00:01:31.940
and fonts of your application.

00:01:31.940 --> 00:01:38.940
So here I've set the background and foreground colors to a dark mode for my application.

00:01:38.940 --> 00:01:43.400
And then next, I could choose to set some important accent colors, like the primary

00:01:43.400 --> 00:01:45.019
or secondary color.

00:01:45.019 --> 00:01:50.220
And finally, I will set a different base font from the Bootstrap defaults.

00:01:50.220 --> 00:01:54.820
So here I'm going to use the font Google function, which does a lot of work for me

00:01:54.820 --> 00:02:00.260
in terms of making sure that the font files are available for the end user, even if they

00:02:00.260 --> 00:02:02.779
don't have an internet connection.

00:02:02.779 --> 00:02:07.820
And also keep in mind with this bstheme function, you have access to hundreds of different more

00:02:07.820 --> 00:02:13.059
specific styling settings if you want to get more targeted with your styles.

00:02:13.059 --> 00:02:18.500
And to quickly preview a given theme object, try out this bstheme preview function, which

00:02:18.500 --> 00:02:23.460
essentially runs a demo app where you can see all the various components that your theme

00:02:23.460 --> 00:02:25.539
might impact.

00:02:25.539 --> 00:02:31.419
Now if you were to include a bstheme object inside of your own application, you might

00:02:31.419 --> 00:02:37.419
notice that the styling of your application doesn't propagate to the static R plots that

00:02:37.419 --> 00:02:40.139
are generated by your Shiny app.

00:02:40.139 --> 00:02:43.779
And this is one of the reasons why we created the thematic package.

00:02:43.779 --> 00:02:49.139
If you call this thematic Shiny function just prior to running the Shiny application,

00:02:49.139 --> 00:02:54.860
then all of the static R plots that are generated by the Shiny app will use the CSS styles on

00:02:54.860 --> 00:02:59.740
their container to set new theming defaults on the R side.

00:02:59.740 --> 00:03:04.259
BSLib also provides an interactive theming tool, which allows you to quickly try out

00:03:04.259 --> 00:03:10.600
different theme settings and seeing how that theme renders in real time.

00:03:10.600 --> 00:03:17.580
This theming tool can be used with any Shiny application by calling the bsthemer function.

00:03:17.580 --> 00:03:23.240
The only requirements is that you call the bsthemer function inside of the server function

00:03:23.240 --> 00:03:28.639
and that you're using this interactive themer with Bootstrap 4.

00:03:28.639 --> 00:03:32.759
Also keep in mind that if you're running this themer locally, any of the interactive changes

00:03:32.759 --> 00:03:37.440
that you make are captured with R code and emitted to your R console so that you can

00:03:37.440 --> 00:03:41.000
copy-paste those changes into your theme creation.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:45.199
Now if you'd like to use these theming tools with R Markdown, the first thing to know is

00:03:45.199 --> 00:03:51.160
that you can pass these theme settings into the theme parameter of an HTML document.

00:03:51.160 --> 00:03:55.960
In addition, if you'd like to theme your document with the interactive theming tool, you'll

00:03:55.960 --> 00:04:01.919
have to first add a Shiny runtime to your document's YAML matter and then call the bsthemer

00:04:01.919 --> 00:04:04.839
function inside of the server side code.

00:04:04.839 --> 00:04:09.679
Now if you'd like these real-time changes in the CSS on the page to influence the R

00:04:09.679 --> 00:04:15.679
plots rendered by the document, you'll first have to enable thematic and then also make

00:04:15.679 --> 00:04:19.559
sure that you're rendering your plots through Shiny's render plot.

00:04:19.559 --> 00:04:24.040
It's also worth noting that thematic can be used anywhere to create any sort of file format

00:04:24.040 --> 00:04:26.079
that you want.

00:04:26.079 --> 00:04:33.160
We've seen it used with Shiny in our Markdown's HTML document to create PNG images where the

00:04:33.160 --> 00:04:37.279
styles are automatically informed by CSS styles.

00:04:37.279 --> 00:04:43.519
However, you can also enable thematic and give it the actual color codes for a background,

00:04:43.519 --> 00:04:49.959
foreground, and accent color similar to how we provided those things to a bstheme object.

00:04:49.959 --> 00:04:53.679
And finally, I would like to thank you for listening as well as provide these links to

00:04:53.679 --> 00:04:57.640
the slides as well as documentation where you can learn more.

00:04:57.640 --> 00:04:58.320
Thank you.

